 Pantheisticon -- t9 Philosophical Clandestine Literature and Academic Circles in France -- t10 Joseph as the Natural Father of Christ: An Unknown, Clandestine Manuscript of the Early Eighteenth Century -- t11 Clandestine Philosophical Manuscripts in the Catalogue of Marc-Michel Rey -- tPART FIVE TOLERATION, CRITICISM, AND INNOVATION IN RELIGION -- t12 The Treatise of the Three Impostors, Islam, the Enlightenment, and Toleration -- t13 The Polyvalence of Heterodox Sources and Eighteenth-Century Religious Change -- tPart Six: Spanish Developments -- t14 The Spanish Revolution of 1820-1823 and the Clandestine Philosophical Literature -- t15 A Clandestine Manuscript in the Vernacular: An 1822 Spanish Translation of the Examen critique of 1733 -- tAfterword -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tTHE UCLA CLARK MEMORIAL LIBRARY SERIES0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aClandestine philosophical manuscripts, made up of forbidden works including erotic texts, political pamphlets, satires of court life, forbidden religious texts, and books about the occult, had an avid readership in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, becoming objects of historical research by the twentieth century. The purveyors of the clandestine could be found in the Dutch Republic, Switzerland, Denmark, Spain, and not least in Paris or London. Despite the heavy risks, including prison, the circulation of these manuscripts was a prosperous venture. After Ira Wade's pioneering contribution (1938), Clandestine Philosophy is the first work in English entirely focused on the philosophical clandestine manuscripts that preceded and accompanied the birth of the Enlightenment. Topics from philosophy, political and religious thought, and moral and sexual behaviour are addressed by contemporary authors working in both America and Europe. These manuscripts shed light on the birth of pornography and provide an important avenue for investigating philosophical, religious, political, and social critique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aManuscripts, EuropeanvCongressesxHistoryy17th century. 0aManuscripts, EuropeanvCongressesxHistoryy18th century. 0aManuscripts, EuropeanvCongressesxHistoryy19th century. 0aManuscripts, EuropeanxHistoryy17th centuryvCongresses. 0aManuscripts, EuropeanxHistoryy18th centuryvCongresses. 0aManuscripts, EuropeanxHistoryy19th centuryvCongresses. 0aPhilosophy (General). 0aPhilosophy, ModernvCongressesxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, ModernxHistoryvCongresses. 0aUnderground literaturevCongressesxHistory and criticismzEurope. 0aUnderground literaturevCongressesxManuscriptszEurope. 0aUnderground literaturezEuropexHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aUnderground literaturezEuropexManuscriptsvCongresses. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aRenaissance.  aclandestine.  acourt life.  aearly modern philosophy.  aerotic.  aforbidden religious texts.  ahistory of philosophy.  aliterature.  amanuscript studies.  amanuscripts.  aoccult.  apamphlets.  aphilosophy.  apolitica.  areligion.  asatires.  asubversive.  atexts.1 aBunge, Wiep Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurson, Jeffrey D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollewand, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsrael, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacob, Margaret C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJacob, Margaret C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaursen, Jo